definition.value: The L-enantiomer of ornithinium(2+).
An adenosine 3'-phosphate that is ADP carrying a phospate group at the 3'-position. It is potent inhibitor of bovine pancreatic ribonuclease A.
An N(5)-acyl-L-ornithine in which the the acyl group is specified as acetyl.
A 2-amino-2-deoxy-D-glucopyranose with an alpha-configuration at the anomeric position.
A derivative of octanoic acid carrying a beta-oxo group; a possible metabolite of 2-octynoic acid.
A 1-phenylpropan-2-amine that has S configuration.
The hydroxamate of phosphonoacetic acid.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine having a dodecanoyl group at the 1-position and a pentacosanoyl group at the 2-position.

A 6-methoxy-11-methyl-1,3,4,9,10,10a-hexahydro-2H-10,4a-(epiminoethano)phenanthrene in which the sterocenters at positions 4a, 10 and 10a have S-configuration. It is a prodrug of dextrorphan and used as an antitussive drug for suppressing cough.
The hydrobromide and monohydrate of the antitussive drug dextromethorphan.

An L-phenylalanine derivative that is L-phenylalanine substituted by a benzoyl group at position 4. It is a photoreactive unnatural amino acid that acts as a photo cross-linking probe when incorporated into proteins.
A pyridinedicarboxylic acid carrying carboxy groups at positions 2 and 4.

(7S,8S)-7-Amino-8-methyl-5,6,7,8-tetrahydronaphthalen-2-ol in which the hydrogen at position 8 and one of the hydrogens at position 6 are substituted by each end of a tetramethylene bridge. A synthetic opioid analgesic, it has mixed opiod agonist and antagonist properties. Although it is used for pain management, it can produce opioid withdrawal syndrome in patients already dependent on other opioids, and its clinical application is limited by side effects such as dizziness.
A D-alanine derivative arising from reductive N-alkylation of D-alanine by pyridoxal-5-phosphate.
A dihydroxyphenylacetic acid having the two hydroxy substituents at the 2- and 5-positions.
A hydroxypolyether aldehyde comprising hexaethylene glycol having one of the terminal hydroxy groups substituted by formylmethoxy.
An L-lysine derivative arising from reductive alkylation of the N(2)-position of L-lysine by pyridoxal-5-phosphate.
A hydroxypolyether phosphate consisting of hexaethylene glycol carrying a single O-phospho group.
An alanine derivative arising from reductive N-alkylation of L-alanine by pyridoxal-5-phosphate.
A xanthene dye having two fluoro substituents at the 2- and 7-positions and a 2,4-dicarboxyphenyl group at the 9-position.
A poly(ethylene glycol) containing 14 ethyleneoxy units.
A ketoxime obtained via formal condensation of butane-2,3-dione with hydroxylamine. It is a reversible myosin ATPase inhibitor.
A tetrahydroxytetrahydrofuran in which the hydroxy groups are located at positions 2, 3, 4, and 4 and which is substituted by a methyl group at position 2 (the 2R,4S diastereoisomer).
